Respiratory system regulates blood gases

Arterial O2, CO2and H+are primary determinants of breathing

Peripheral and central chemoreceptors

Consider hypercapnia, hypoxemia, and/ or acidosis what happens to respiration?

2 locations:

Aortic arch aortic bodies

Carotid arteries carotid bodies

Send signals to VRG via vagusnerve (aortic) and glossopharyngeal nerve (carotid)

Results in increase in respiration!

Central chemoreceptors

Found in ventrolateral medulla behind blood brain barrier

Detect changes in pH (and therefore CO2)

CO2 in the blood diffuses into the cerebrospinal fluid where it is hydrated consider equation!

Respond more rapidly to arterial CO2and brain extracellular H+than to arterial H+

Also:

Peripheral chemoreceptors are the sole driver in response to hypoxemia (O2)

The airways and lungs (from larynx to lungs) are densely innervated by sensory neurons arising from the vagusnerve.

They constantly monitor the airway environment and send this information to the brainstem (medulla) the nucleus of the solitary tract (NTS)

This drives motor actions including changes in breathing, reflex cough responses, and changes in vasculature and gland secretions etc. ALL TO KEEP US ALIVE!!
